<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910429-0007</DOCNO><DOCID>910429-0007.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>04/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   OPEC'S OIL OUTPUT is falling for the first time sinceAugust, perhaps by more than the amount the group's oilministers agreed on. But world crude supplies remain high andany price rise may be short-lived.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Bush's push for lower world interest rates failed to winmuch support from other major industrial nations at a meetingof finance officials.   ---   The U.S. economy shrank at a 2.8% annual rate in the firstquarter after contracting at a 1.6% rate in the fourthquarter. But the Bush administration held to its view thatgrowth may return in the next few months.                                                                                                          U.S. machine tool orders dropped 16.2% in March fromFebruary. Most of the decline came from overseas.   ---   General Cinema withdrew its $1.1 billion offer forHarcourt bonds but didn't abandon hope for a deal. The priceof the bonds fell little after the theater concern'sannouncement.   ---   Ford plans to cut its European white-collar staff byroughly 30%, or about 6,300 people, over three years.   ---   ATandamp;T and NCR reported progress toward an accord on thephone giant's bid to acquire the computer maker.   ---   Banks should pay a special assessment to bolster thedeposit insurance fund, the General Accounting Office urged.But the industry said the move would worsen the creditcrunch.   ---   The U.S. moved to bar Japan from bidding on federallyfunded construction projects and cited China, India andThailand for inadequate protection of intellectual-propertyrights.   ---   Visa said it offered to pay the legal costs of a group ofBoston restaurants in their revolt against American Express,but said there was nothing illegal or unethical about theoffer.   ---   A KKR partnership plans to buy nine publications fromRupert Murdoch's News Corp. for $650 million.   ---   Procter andamp; Gamble decided to remove the word &quot;fresh&quot; frompackages of its Citrus Hill orange juice, under pressure fromthe FDA.   ---   Harsh sentencing guidelines for punishing corporatewrongdoing were approved by a federal commission, clearingthe way for a congressional battle over their adoption.   ---   America West posted a widened loss of $49.9 million forthe first quarter, and SEC filings show the airline defaultedon certain loan covenants.   ---   J.P. Morgan is halting its processing of shares in SouthAfrican companies amid objections from municipal and stateunderwriting customers.   ---   Shell Oil's first-quarter profit sank 39%, in contrast tobig increases posted by other oil companies.   ---   Mitsubishi Electric agreed to sell under its own labelminicomputers and mainframes made by IBM.   ---   Sunbelt Savings FSB was placed in conservatorship in thegovernment's latest step in a three-year effort to sell theTexas institution.   ---   Advanced Micro Devices plans to unveil today a clone ofIntel's most popular personal-computer chip.   ---   Markets--   Stocks: Volume 153,860,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2912.38, off 8.66; transportation 1166.08, off 4.05;utilities 209.82, up 0.44.   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3777.35, up 10.03.   Commodities: Oil $21.28 a barrel, up 13 cents. Dow Jonesfutures index 127.41, off 0.30; spot index 126.62, up 0.28.   Dollar: 138.10 yen, up 0.27; 1.7510 marks, up 0.0025.</TEXT></DOC>